Why its companions were suffered to perish, or designedly destroyed, we nre lest to conjecture, in the silence of history and the absence of evidence. But that this was not always an insulated and solitary document, that there were in fact rolls extending through the whole reign of Henry 1.. and probably back to the period when first the Court of Exchequer was established, we have, in addition to the probabilities in the case, the sufficient evidence of Sweresord‚ the compiler of the Red Book of the Exchequer, who, in a passage cited by Madox, says, that he had himself inspected n few of the Annual Rolls of that reign.

Of a record so antient and valuable as this much use has been made by antiquarian, legal, and histo- rical writers, under all the disadvaumges attending the means of access. And among the peculiarities of this interesting document, it occurs now to he mentioned, that very discordant opinions have been maintained respecting the year, and even the reign, to which it belongs. Like most other early docu- ments of the English monarchy, this roll was pre- pared without any contemporary and authoritative declaration of the time when the accompts which it contains were rendered.
